    "narrative": "For today\u2019s slate, our lineup construction prioritizes high-efficiency matchups against favorable opposing rotations. **Mickey Moniak** leads the charge with an elite 75.98 efficiency score, bolstered by a juicy matchup against Buehler. While his raw base is steady, the combination of a favorable platoon and Buehler\u2019s slow delivery\u2014providing a +2% bump for **Mickey Moniak**\u2019s stolen base upside\u2014makes him our anchor. Similarly, **Brice Turang** earns a 75.06 rating, utilizing a prime leadoff spot and a +19% skill advantage over Irvin to maximize our pursuit of speed. We also see high-floor production from **Vinnie Pasquantino** (72.92) and **Josh Naylor** (64.69); both benefit from strong lineup positioning and favorable park factors, though we must keep a close eye on the 31% rain risk clouding **Vinnie Pasquantino**\u2019s outlook in what could become a truncated appearance.\n\nThe most difficult decision on the bench was leaving **Alex Freeland** (50.90) on the outside looking in. **Alex Freeland** actually outscored our C1, **Gabriel Moreno** (49.27), on a pure efficiency basis, but the positional versatility requirements and our strategic need for **Gabriel Moreno**\u2019s specific lineup slot dictated the final roster. We also weighed the heavy-hitting profiles of **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** and **Giancarlo Stanton** against the lefty Matz; however, their respective scores plummeted due to significant platoon disadvantages, cementing their roles as reserves today. \n\nWe are monitoring the **James Wood** situation closely; while his 50.18 score is marginal, his elite speed profile against the slow-delivering Ashby provides a necessary floor in our pursuit of stolen bases. Conversely, **Max Muncy** (51.78) remains a risky start, as the combination of a difficult matchup against the elite hold profile of Holmes\u2014who effectively suppresses baserunning\u2014and a #7 spot in the order creates a \"below floor\" hazard. While **Austin Riley** (61.27) and **Tyler Soderstrom** (63.69) provide stable mid-tier production, the success of Ghost Ride the WHIP today rests on our ability to capitalize on these specific platoon advantages and the high-leverage stolen base opportunities created by the opposing pitching staff\u2019s delivery patterns.",
